        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer315736306" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6721148950407376514">Candida Pugh spoke recently at a wonderful women&apos;s organization (The Women&apos;s Exchange) located in the north suburbs of Chicago. I didn&apos;t have the chance to hear her talk, but a friend attended and shared her copy of Pugh&apos;s novel with me. Fascinating story. I&apos;m younger than Pugh, but I&apos;ve always thought I knew a good deal about the Freedom Rides of the early 60&apos;s . Well, from reading this I quickly learned that my insight was limited, but this &apos;fictionalized memoir&apos; is filling in many of my gaps.</span>
  <span id="freeText6721148950407376514" style="display:none">Candida Pugh spoke recently at a wonderful women's organization (The Women's Exchange) located in the north suburbs of Chicago. I didn't have the chance to hear her talk, but a friend attended and shared her copy of Pugh's novel with me. Fascinating story. I'm younger than Pugh, but I've always thought I knew a good deal about the Freedom Rides of the early 60's . Well, from reading this I quickly learned that my insight was limited, but this 'fictionalized memoir' is filling in many of my gaps...<br /><br />The material is painful, but important, the narration believable and skillfully crafted, the characters well-drawn and compelling.<br /><br />Definitely a must-read for anyone who wants a better sense of race relations, past and present.</span>
